properties.States: Jammu and Kashmir, Himachal Pradesh, Punjab, Rajasthan, Haryana,Union Territory of Chandigarh
properties.Ba_Positio: It is lies in Tibet, India, Pkistan Afghanistan. It is bounded on North by the Karakoram & Harakoram ranges, East Himalayas, west Sulaiman & Kirthar ranges, South Arabian Sea
properties.Ba_Physiog: The upper part of the basin mostly mountain ranges and narrow valleys. In Punjab, Haryana and Rajasthan the basin consists of vast plains. Soil types are submontane, brown hill and alluvial soils.

properties.Ba_Positio: It is bounded on the north and north-west by the Aravalli hills, on the east by the ridge separating it from the Chambal basin, on the south by the Vindhyas and on the west by the Gulf of Cambay.
properties.Ba_Physiog: Upper part mostly hills and forests except the lower half in M.P., which is fairly plain.The lower part of the basin lying in Gujarat is flat and fertile and well developed alluvial tract. Imprtant soil types in the basin are red and black soils.

properties.Ba_Positio: It is bounded on the north and northeast by the Aravalli hills, on the east by the Mahi basin, on the south by the Gulf of Cambay and on the west by the basins of minor streams draining into Rann of Kuch and the Gulf of Cambay.
properties.Ba_Physiog: The important soil types found in the basin are black, alluvial and sandy soils.

properties.States: Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, Gujarat and Maharashtra
properties.Ba_Positio: It is bounded on the north by the Vindhyas, on the east by the Maikala range, on the south by the Satpuras and on the west by the Arabian Sea.
properties.Ba_Physiog: It can be divided into hilly and plain regions. The hilly regions are in the upper part of the basin. The plain regions in between the hilly tracts and in the lower reaches are broad and fertile.Soil typeas are black soils, alluvial clays.

properties.Ba_Positio: It is bounded on the north by the Satpura range, on the east by the Mahadeo hills, on the south by the Ajanata range and the Satmal hills and on the west by the Arabian Sea.
properties.Ba_Physiog: Two physical regions in the basin-namely, hilly region and the plains. The hilly regions comprising Satpura, Satmalas, Ajanta and Gawilgarh hills are well forested. The plain areas are broad and fertile. Primarily black soils and alluvial clays.

properties.States: Uttaranchal, Uttar Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgar, Bihar, jharkhand, Rajasthan, West Bengal, Haryana, Himachal Pradesh,Union Territory of Delhi
properties.Ba_Positio: Ganga Basin lies in India, Tibet, Nepal & Bangladesh. It is bounded on north by the  Himalayas, West Aravalis, South Vindhas  & Chhotanagpur plateaus, East Brahmaputra ridge.
properties.Ba_Physiog: Northern Mountains comprises the Himalayan ranges including their foothills.The Genetic plains situated between the Himalayas and the Deccan plateau. The Central highlands lying to the south of the Great plains consists of mountains, hills and plateaus.

properties.States: Arunachal Pradesh, Assam, Nagaland, Meghalaya, West Bengal and Sikkim
properties.Ba_Positio: Brahmaputra basin lies in Tibet, Bhutan, India and Bangladesh. it is bounded on North by the Himalayas, East Patkari range, South Assam range, West Himalayas
properties.Ba_Physiog: Upper part of the  basin is mostly mountain ranges and narrow valleys. Most portion in Assam, Meghalaya, West Bengal consists of hills.Cooch Bihar, West Dinajpur districts have fertile plains. Soil types are red loamy, alluvial, sandy, loamy, clay soils.

properties.States: Meghalaya, Manipur, Mizoram, Assam, Tripura and Nagaland
properties.Ba_Positio: Barak sub-basin drains areas in India, Bangladesh and Burma. It is bounded on the north by the Barail range, East Naga and Lushai hills and South and West Bangladesh.
properties.Ba_Physiog: Two major physiographic regions namely, the hilly region and the plains. The predominant soil types found in the sub-basin are laterite and red and yellow soils.

properties.States: Meghalaya, Manipur, Mizoram, Assam, Tripura and Nagaland
properties.Ba_Positio: Barak sub-basin drains areas in India, Bangladesh and Burma. It is bounded on the north by the Barail range, East Naga and Lushai hills and South and West Bangladesh.
properties.Ba_Physiog: Two major physiographic regions namely, the hilly region and the plains. The predominant soil types found in the sub-basin are laterite and red and yellow soils.
properties.BA_NAME: Minor rivers draining into Bangladesh Basin

properties.States: Maharashtra, Andhra Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, Orissa, Karnataka and Chhattisgarh
properties.Ba_Positio: It is bounded on the north by the Satmala Hills, the Ajanta Range and the Mahadeo Hills, on the east and south by the Eastern Ghats and on the west by the Western Ghats.
It is bounded on the north by the Godavari basin, on the south and east by the Eastern Ghats and on the west by the Western Ghats.
properties.Ba_Physiog: Most part comprises rolling and undulating country except the western border, which is formed by an unbroken line of the Western Ghats. Soil types are black soils, red soils, literite soils, alluvium, red and black soil and saline and alkaline soils.

properties.Ba_Positio: It is bounded on the west by the Western Ghats, on the east and south by the Eastern Ghats and on the north by the Tungabhadra and Pennar basins.
properties.Ba_Physiog: It is divided into three parts- Westen Ghats, Plateau of Mysore & Delta. The delta area is the most fertile tract in the basin.Soil types are black soils, red soils, laterites, alluvial soils, forest soils and mixed soils.

properties.Ba_Positio: It is bounded on the north by the Chhotanagpur Plateau, on the west and south by the ridge separating it from Mahandi basin and on the east by the Bay of Bengal.
properties.Ba_Physiog: Four well-defined regions - northern plateau, Eastern Ghats, coastal plains and central tableland. First two regions are mostly hilly and forested. Soil types are red and yellow, red sandy and loamy soils and coastal alluvium.

properties.States: Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, Orissa, Jharkhand and Maharashtra
properties.Ba_Positio: It is bounded on the north by the Central India Hills, on the south and east by the Eastern Ghats and on the west by the Maikala range.
properties.Ba_Physiog: The basin can be divided into four regions, namely, the Northen Plateau, the Eastern Ghats, the Coastal Plain and the erosional plains of Central Table Land. Soil types are red and yellow soils, laterite soils, and deltaic soils.

properties.Ba_Positio: It is bounded on the north by the Erramala range, east by the Nallamala and velikonda ranges of the Eastern Ghats, south by the Nandidurg hills and west by the Vedavati valley of the Krishna basin.
properties.Ba_Physiog: The important soil types are red soils, black soil, sandy soil and mixed soil.
